-**Distinguishing confirmatory from novel contributions.** The factor-by-factor agreement reported above with prior single-method or single-discipline studies represents the confirmatory component of the present work. The novel component, in contrast, lies in three results that, to our knowledge, are not jointly available in the existing B2B order-success literature: (i) a scorer-neutral, scale-invariant ranking rule – the modified Borda mean rank of Eq. (3) – whose properties (methodological neutrality, scale invariance, robustness to outliers in individual scorer outputs, interpretational clarity) are explicitly argued for, rather than implicitly assumed; (ii) a cross-scorer stability perspective, in which a feature is considered a fundamental determinant only when its rank is consistent across mathematically heterogeneous feature significance scorers, providing a complementary criterion to predictive accuracy; and (iii) the negative finding that, in a well-organized ERP-based B2B environment, discount-related and fine-grained temporal variables – each individually dominant in adjacent literatures – are statistically dominated by relational variables, with the inverted U-shape of order\_amount mechanistically explaining the divergence of single-method rankings on this feature.  
-**Theoretical implications.** The results align with, and provide cross-scorer evidence for, a relational view of B2B transactions, in which the probability of order completion is governed primarily by the quality and intensity of dyadic interaction rather than by transactional or temporal context. From a methodological standpoint, the modified Borda mean rank introduces a quantifiable notion of cross-scorer stability as a reliability criterion: features whose ranks vary substantially across scorers (e.g., ‘order\_amount’) are not necessarily uninformative, but their predictive contribution is non-monotonic and scorer-sensitive, and should therefore be treated with scorer-aware care. This complements the predictive-accuracy criterion that dominates ML-driven sales forecasting (Rohaan et al., 2022; Bauskar, 2024\) with a robustness-of-importance criterion, addressing the divided-opinions issue identified in Section 2\.  
-**Practical implications.** Operationally, the proposed method translates into a generic integration pattern for ERP-based decision-support modules: (i) the five feature significance scorers are run on the pre-processed feature matrix; (ii) the resulting ranks are consolidated via Eq. (3); and (iii) the consolidated ranking, together with a cross-scorer stability index defined as the standard deviation of per-scorer ranks for each monitored feature, is exposed to managerial dashboards as a feature-importance scoring layer over the order pipeline (in Odoo, for instance, on top of ‘sale.order’ records). When instantiated on the analyzed dataset, this pattern produces the dataset-specific ranking reported in Table 1 and discussed above; when applied to another ERP deployment or B2B segment, it is expected to yield a different factor ordering, and the same method can be used to quantify which features remain consistently important across scorers for that particular dataset. The prescriptive content of this study is therefore the method itself, together with the cross-scorer stability criterion, rather than any universal list of B2B success factors.  
